<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-02-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="220" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d220">
                    <head>No. 216.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Noyes</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Evarts</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-02-21"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 21,
                            1881</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>Short interview with minister for foreign affairs to-day. Have another
                        to-morrow. Nothing decisive. Minister says decree was issued under pressure
                        of public opinion. Shall insist firmly upon revocation.</p>
                    <closer><signed>NOYES.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>